  <section class="faq-section">
    <div class="container">
      <div class="section-header"><span class="section-tag">Got Questions?</span><h2>SIP Calculator — FAQs</h2><p>Common questions about SIP investing.</p></div>
      <div class="faq-list">
        <div class="faq-item"><button class="faq-question">Is 12% return realistic for SIP?<i class="fas fa-chevron-down"></i></button><div class="faq-answer"><div class="faq-answer-inner">Historically, equity mutual funds in India have delivered 12-15% CAGR over 10+ year periods. Large-cap funds average around 11-13%, while mid/small-cap funds have delivered 14-18%. However, returns are not guaranteed and depend on market conditions. For conservative planning, use 10-12% for equity SIPs.</div></div></div>
        <div class="faq-item"><button class="faq-question">Can I stop or pause my SIP?<i class="fas fa-chevron-down"></i></button><div class="faq-answer"><div class="faq-answer-inner">Yes, SIPs are flexible. You can pause, stop, or modify your SIP amount at any time without penalties. Most fund houses allow pausing for 1-3 months. You can also redeem your accumulated units partially or fully at any time (after any applicable exit load period, typically 1 year for equity funds).</div></div></div>
        <div class="faq-item"><button class="faq-question">What is the minimum SIP amount?<i class="fas fa-chevron-down"></i></button><div class="faq-answer"><div class="faq-answer-inner">Most mutual funds allow SIPs starting from ₹500 per month, and some even from ₹100. There's no maximum limit. The key is to start early and be consistent — even ₹500/month for 30 years at 12% grows to over ₹17.6 lakhs from just ₹1.8 lakhs invested.</div></div></div>
        <div class="faq-item"><button class="faq-question">SIP vs lump sum — which is better?<i class="fas fa-chevron-down"></i></button><div class="faq-answer"><div class="faq-answer-inner">SIP is better for most investors because: (1) it doesn't require a large upfront amount, (2) rupee cost averaging reduces timing risk, (3) it builds investing discipline. Lump sum can be better if you have a large amount and markets are at a low point. For salaried individuals, SIP aligned with salary date is the most practical approach.</div></div></div>
        <div class="faq-item"><button class="faq-question">How is SIP taxed?<i class="fas fa-chevron-down"></i></button><div class="faq-answer"><div class="faq-answer-inner">Each SIP instalment is treated as a separate investment for tax purposes. For equity funds, gains on units held over 1 year are Long-Term Capital Gains (LTCG) — tax-free up to ₹1.25 lakh per year, and 12.5% beyond that. Short-term gains (under 1 year) are taxed at 20%. ELSS SIPs also offer ₹1.5 lakh deduction under Section 80C with a 3-year lock-in.</div></div></div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="page-content" style="padding-top:0;"><div class="container"><div class="page-cta"><div><h3>Start Building Wealth Today</h3><p>Begin your SIP journey with as little as ₹500/month and watch compounding work its magic.</p></div><a href="/pages/contact" class="btn btn-outline" style="color:#fff;border:2px solid rgba(255,255,255,0.5);padding:14px 32px;font-size:0.95rem;">Start SIP <i class="fas fa-arrow-right"></i></a></div></div></section>

